The house of the bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. The interiors of Gaudí are observed
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lagoon, the stairs remind the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Batlló House in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Because of its similar shape to a skeleton, the locals seized it "the house of the bones".
Its organic shapes, its appealing colors, the innovative use of the stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade that recalls the scales and omnipresent gently curved lines, all this is typical of Antoni Gaudí's secession.
The cover of the house plays with oniric lines, delicate colors and textures extracted from nature and fauna.
By paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm, and a carefully thought - out order are observed.
At night, the whole facade of the house seems even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
The snake and the torsion of the shapes continues to surprise us also within it.
The walled wood copies the frames of the windows, the rocks, the decorations of the doors, the mirrors and the letters.
The Batlló House, which is located in the Eixample district in number 43 of the animated shopping street of Passeig de Gràcia, arose from the remodelling of a house in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on breaking down the previous building and starting at zero, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of making a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Batlló House, made up of several apartments, did not design it by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in their plans of the project there were decorations for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
In the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of the Batlló House was the beginning of the successful collaboration of Jujol with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of the Mila House and the Güell Park of Gaudí, where other parts of it are located.
Because of its organic form, the premises soon after its completion seized it "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows, began to call it "the house of drawers".
It is also said that, at the height of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for central heating time with ventilation ventilators and typical fireplaces.
It may turn out to be a strange slope of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not comply at all with the construction standards of the moment and was not allowed to be influenced by them.
Still, the construction was granted the relevant permit from the beginning, although obviously the data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town council was so affected by the result requested to be corrected.
He was upset, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public steel.
The arrangements were never made, on the contrary: only fifteen days after the city's request, Josep Batlló requested permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
The owner himself was installed on the lower floors.
In the gallery of the second floor there was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelery.
The house, with six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the terrace of the roof.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all right angles and lines, covering them from curved walls.
Gaudí also worked on the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the halls and a larger group can be communicated in this way without problems, without giving up the necessary privacy for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white tiles and blues that cover the inner courtyard and tragaluces.
The game with the two colors provides the maximum light on all the floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that the white reflects more light than the dark colors, which on the contrary absorb the rays of the sun.
Anyone can visit the Batlló House, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment available to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it was a very beneficial business and extended the visits to the common area and to the busherilla, including the terrace of the roof.
The price of entry to the monument is not insignificant, reaching EUR 16.50, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get 20% discount.
The amount exceeds significantly the price of the entry of other buildings of Gaudí in the city.
