Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as support for private companies.
Crime is more of a concern than unemployment.
In addition, in much of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the last Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been carried out regularly since 1995, it enables monitoring of changes in attitudes in the region.
The results of this year's survey, carried out in September and early October, highlight two related issues.
The first is the relatively animated humour ruling in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes to democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the coast of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent a year since 2002, support for democracy has increased from 40 per cent in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
He also grew up in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a great decline in production last year.
However, only half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced Democrats, which lowers the regional average (see Figure 2).
Around 44 per cent of respondents in the region expressed satisfaction with the way democracy works in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but significantly higher than 25 per cent recorded in 2001 (Graph 3).
About 34 per cent said they trusted the Congress of their country and 45 per cent in their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but significantly higher in 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America seriously affected support for democracy.
The fact that it has been maintained during the global financial crisis is probably due to the fact that many Latin American countries have only been affected by a brief recession and have enjoyed a strong recovery.
In addition, the existence of a stronger social security network has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin American people living in poverty was only marginally increased in 2009 and that it has been reduced again this year, up to 32 per cent.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see Figure 4).
Brazil's good economic performance and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where the recession was more severe and violent crimes have increased.
For the second time since the surveys began, the most surveyed in Latin America mention crime, instead of unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see Figure 5).
About 31 per cent claims that either they or a close relative have been the victim of crime in the past year, a figure that has been reduced since 38 per cent of last year and that it is the lowest percentage recorded since 1995.
The most positive economic performance is reflected in greater support for private enterprises and the market economy: about 71 per cent of respondents in the region claim that private enterprises are indispensable for development, while only 56 per cent in 2007 (see Figure 6).
Around 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow its country to develop, compared with 47% last year.
It is interesting that 62% of the respondents in Venezuela feel the same way (and 80% support private companies), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the country that exercises greater leadership in the region, as indicated by 19% of respondents (18% last year), followed by the United States (9%, the same figure last year) and Venezuela (9% compared to 11% a year ago).
However, the United States is the country considered most influential by the surveyed in Mexico and much of Central America, while Venezuela holds such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
