In a particular classroom that was slightly illuminated, with walls painted and discolored, the principal of the Second School Anlong Veng reminded the man who had built it, the last leader of the Red Jemeres Ta Mok.
"This is where everyone loves Ta Mok."
"He was a good leader and was concerned about his people," said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the Carnicero" because of its brutality during the Red Jemeres government, the commander is still popular in this remote ex fort of the Red Jemeres in northwest Cambodia, where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructures, and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Red Jemeres surrender to the government, the long-lasting loyalty is finally being challenged in Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum for truth and reconciliation enabled victims to face publicly those who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed here a textbook of secondary school which for the first time teaches the story of the Red Jemeres to the children of their former soldiers.
And in July, a United Nations-Cambodia Joint Court issued the first sentence of a former member of the Red Jemeres, judging the former head of the known Tuol Slang torture centre, Kaing Khek Iev, best known as Duch, at 35 years of imprisonment.
With each of these events, anxiety has grown among the veterans of the Red Jemeres of Anlong Veng, complicated efforts for reconciliation and their attempts to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
"There is resentment and fear among the former Red Jemeres, but they can't do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodian Documentation Centre, an independent organization that investigates the regime.
"For them, life under the Red Jemeres was glorious, but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"This is generating divisions within families."
During the Government of the Red Jemeres of Cambodia, between 1975 and 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When in 1979 the Vietnamese invaded and defeated the government led by Pol Pot, the rest of the regime and its soldiers fled to the Cambodian border with Thailand.
There they launched an insurrection that lasted until the last movement that was surrendered in December 1998.
As Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the war of guerrillas from their bases in the mountains and forests of western Cambodia, Ta Mok cultivated followers in Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a peace agreement sponsored by the United Nations led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Red Jemeres fighters began to desert the government, culminating in Ieng Sary's returns in 1996, and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998, and Ta Mok, who had resisted, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the nearby Dangrek Mountains.
He died in a prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 while awaiting trial.
Without the support of its benefactors, the oldest Red Jemers fighters fell into the absolute misery that is common in rural Cambodia, and many feel nostalgia for the movement.
Although few Red Jemeres elite officials have retained their local administrative positions instead of depositing their weapons, racial soldiers remain poor and unqualified farmers.
"These people have gained little benefit after surrender," Sok Lang of the Centre for Justice and Reconciliation said, which offers public forums throughout Cambodia, even in Anlong Veng.
"They have incorporated the utopian agricultural ideology of the regime."
"They were created without any concept of business."
Sister Lim, 55, who joined the Red Jemeres when she was a teenager in 1974, fought in the forest near Anlong Veng before being dedicated to life as a poor rice farmer in 1998.
"Life with the Red Jemeres was good," he said.
"Ta Mok gave her all the food."
"But now life is hard because we have to self-abstain."
The current Red Sea Court has also raised concerns here.
At the beginning of next year, it is expected that the court will begin trialing Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Red Jemeres minister.
The mandate of the court is to prosecute the main leaders and those with greater responsibility for the crimes, but it has not stated whether or not it will pursue cases in addition to those four.
This wasn't much used to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
The recent media speculation has focused on 64-year-old Im Chaem, who was a district chief in the province of Banteay Meanchey during the government of the Red Jemeres in the late 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers from the Cambodian Documentation Centre that she had monitored the construction of Trapeang Thma's dam, a project that was thought to have killed thousands of forced workers.
During a recent rainy afternoon, Im Chaem again worked in the fields at his home on wooden pilots on a dirt road outside Anlong Veng.
When the sun dropped long shadows on the dry past, Im Chaem refused to talk about his past in the Red Jemeres.
She said that if the court called her up, she would not be presented.
"Cambodia is in peace and stability," he said.
"If there are more processings, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who deserted the Red Jemeres in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that there will be instability if the court prosecutes more suspects, although experts and historians question it.
"Cambodia must dig a hole and bury the past," he said.
But facing the past is exactly what Cambodia must do to move forward, Chhang Youk said, from the documentation centre.
"The reconciliation, according to Khmer, is to reunite broken pieces," he said.
"It is our duty to gather these broken pieces so that we can understand."
The centre produced the first text book approved by the government on the Red Jemeres, called "A History of Democratic Kampuchea", of 75 pages.
It was distributed in Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the book of history of secondary school history of the Ministry of Education, which contains less than four pages on the Red Jemeres.
As in most Cambodia, the young people of Anlong Veng know little details about the Red Jemeres, despite the city's link to the regime.
Toque Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng Secondary School, said that the new text book helped students to understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he took the book home to study.
"My family rejects many parts of the text book and the court," he said.
"They have doubts because they are not sure about the number of people the court will prosecute."
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Sok Leang said.
But the public forums, the text book and the court are beginning to produce an impact, he said.
Anyway, here the Red Jemeres preserves a powerful charm.
