At the time of the Obama Nuclear Security Summit, Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko had stated that the nation would never give up its uranium.
"We have preserved the highly enriched uranium ( hundreds of kilograms of what is basically qualified uranium for armament) and the low-rich uranium," Lukashenko said at that time.
"This is our raw material... we're not going to make dirty bombs, and we're not going to sell them to anyone."
"We use it for research purposes, that's all."
However, Belarus approached the United States a few months ago, indicating an interest in reaching an agreement.
Officials said that the first task of withdrawing the uranium from Belarus was particularly complicated in October, as the material had been slightly irradiated.
Officials said it was loaded on a special train that traveled more than 2,000 km to a Russian storage and disposal facility.
According to the officials, the second operation ended on Monday and was made by plane.
The US government spent $13 million on tasks, and most of the money was used to provide Belarus with low-enrichment uranium research, which was not suitable for nuclear weapons.
Andrew Bieniawski, an Energy Department official working in the Global Threat Reduction, said that "this was coordinated and orchestrated with great care to strengthen confidence" which led to the agreement signed by Clinton.
James Martin Center for Non-Proliferation Studies estimated this year that Belarus had at least 40 kilograms of qualified uranium for weapons, as well as hundreds of pounds of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus will try to eliminate its reservation by 2012, according to the joint declaration.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly due to the harsh repression of human rights by Lukashenko.
