The discovery will be presented in a press conference tomorrow Thursday at 1 p.m. at NASA headquarters in Washington by experts in astrobiology, science described as the person responsible for studying the origin, evolution, distribution and the future of life in the Universe.
In quoting to the press, NASA assured that it would present "a finding that would have an impact on the search for extraterrestrial life", which sparked speculation from experts from other countries.
The discovery could demonstrate the theory that there are creatures in our pair and in hostile environments that were thought uninhabitable, and would put on the table the possibility of becoming intelligent beings like humans if they improve the conditions in which they live.
It seems that this is a microbe that was found at the bottom of the Mono Lake in the Yosemite National Park, California, where it lives in an environment that was thought to be too poisonous for any form of life, because the lake is rich in arsenic.
In some ways, the creature uses arsenic as a way of survival and this capacity increases the possibility that similar life could exist on other planets, which do not have our beneficial atmosphere.
According to astrobiologists, if these organisms use arsenic in their metabolism, it will be demonstrated that "if there is another way of life, a second way of life, different from what we know".
The space agency will make known the true reach of the findings at the press conference on Thursday morning.
The conference will be attended by geobiologist Pamela Conrad, who is studying the possibility of life in March; and biologist Steven Benner, one of the scientists who is studying Titan (the largest moon of Saturn), from the perspective that his chemistry is similar to that of the Earth.
