According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bombs, which still monopolies between 50% and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluocompact bombs or, better still, by electroluminescent diodes (DEL or LED) bombs, much of the 1,800 million tonnes of GEI (Gt) emitted on the planet would be avoided to illuminate humans.
Lighting is responsible for 8 per cent of global emissions.
It is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the planetary motor park.
In Copenhagen, last year, large emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce GI global emissions from GI from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, a further 5 Gt of this quantity should be reduced to stabilise, by 2020, the two-degree increase in temperatures to avoid uncontrollable.
In the incandescent pumps, 95% of the energy is dissolved in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. a 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact pumps, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with new LED pumps, energy consumption is reduced twice more.
Fluocompact pumps last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bombs, such as those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80 per cent less energy than an incandescent bomb, which allows us to make an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would apply in one hundred countries.
