On the one hand, they only say what any cultivated person already knows, i.e. that embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of State can be called by phone or catch the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic role and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have become spy centers.
Any viewer who sees research films knows it perfectly, we just seem not to know it because of hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact that it is repeated publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of US diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the secrets of the world's most powerful country significantly affects the prestige of the Department of State.
Therefore, the scandal affects both victims and "virtues".
But we enter into the true nature of what has happened.
In ancient times, in Orwell's time, it could be conceived to all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell's prophecy has come true since, by controlling each movement thanks to the phone, every transaction performed, visited hotel, autopath taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it turns out, as it happens now, that even the encryptions of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, elected as the revenger of citizens) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power be sustained that can no longer keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton's secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power.
