Climate: the French hoods in their financing promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked financing promises (called start-up or early) made by the developed countries have been met.
And the French hoods have been revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed themselves to providing $3 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed itself to EUR 7,200 million in three years and France EUR 1,260 million (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put its best letters on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to the fast-start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press wheel, a large complementary event, the distribution of leaflets...
The transparency operation was a tangible result and was appreciated as it really was: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2,200 million in 2010, which puts it on the right track towards fulfilling its commitment of EUR 7,200 million in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, the money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each one chooses the reference that most suits him.
For example, the European Commission has taken 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million in three years are added to the concept of fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with respect to the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the funding of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, France's total amount of aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while it intends to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the division between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no norm and each one chooses the calculation method.
Some, like France, believe that each euro lent is equivalent to a given euro.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often, projects related to the reduction of emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is a mistake to present a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... As much, only the cost of the loan should be calculated for its commitments for the country granting the loan (i.e. the equivalent of a type of interest).
However, France does not find such reasoning useful: "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million by making 91.5% of loans (EUR 389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (EUR 36.1 million); consult the EU document to see it from its own eyes.
This is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so often.
Germany uses it in 46 per cent, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, inter alia, comply with its commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes a euro to meet its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast-start financing, France commits double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions in time and on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
By spending only EUR 36.1 million, you get the impression that you spend 420 million "new and additional", as you promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has been involved in arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why did the other Member States continue to give when they can just lend) and in the negotiations, since developing countries are not stupid...
The early financing chapter is a small, relatively short-term, relative to the overall climate negotiations.
But it could be an extra sand grains in the enormous machinery that is the CNUC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with a view to respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
However, France could in particular make the debate on long-term financing bets progress (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive about this issue as it is with others.
We therefore hope that the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Koscisko-Morizet, will arrive at Cancún next week.
A surprising announcement on France's fast start and its vision of the "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in the negotiations.
